<DocLayout title="About" description="The AEGIS Initiative — mission, leadership, methodology, and how to support governance-first AI security.">
  <h1>About the AEGIS Initiative</h1>

  <section>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative exists to establish governance-first security as the
      foundational standard for autonomous AI systems. We develop enforceable
      governance frameworks, publish open specifications, and engage with
      policymakers and standards bodies to ensure that AI capability is always
      bounded by constitutional constraint.
    </p>
    <p>
      AEGIS™ is not anti-AI. AEGIS is pro-governance. We believe the path to
      trustworthy AI runs through deterministic enforcement, transparent audit
      trails, and human oversight that cannot be bypassed by the systems it governs.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Mission &amp; Vision</h2>
    <p>
      AEGIS (Autonomous Enforcement Governance for Intelligent Systems) is a
      governance-first security framework for autonomous AI systems. It defines
      enforceable constraints that bind AI capability to human-authorized policy
      at every layer of the stack.
    </p>
    <p>
      AEGIS is not a product. It is a set of specifications, governance documents,
      and reference implementations designed to make AI systems auditable,
      constrained, and transparent by default.
    </p>

    <h3>Founding Principles</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Constraint before capability.</strong> No system should gain capability without corresponding governance.</li>
      <li><strong>Governance before execution.</strong> Policy is evaluated before action, not after.</li>
      <li><strong>Transparency before trust.</strong> Trust is earned through auditable behavior, not declared.</li>
      <li><strong>Oversight before autonomy.</strong> Human authority is the root of all system authority.</li>
      <li><strong>Deny by default.</strong> Anything not explicitly authorized is prohibited.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Non-Partisan Mandate</h3>
    <p>
      AEGIS is non-partisan. Our governance positions are grounded in technical
      analysis, not political alignment. We engage with any policymaker,
      regulator, or standards body — regardless of jurisdiction or political
      orientation — that is working to make AI systems safer, more transparent,
      and more accountable.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/about/mission/">Read more about our mission &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Team &amp; Leadership</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative was founded and is led by <strong>Kenneth Tannenbaum</strong>,
      who serves as Principal, sole maintainer, and the organization's decision-making authority.
    </p>
    <p>
      All governance decisions, architectural choices, and policy positions are
      made by humans. AI tools are used openly and deliberately as productivity
      instruments — for drafting, research, code generation, and analysis. Every
      document, specification, and publication is reviewed, approved, and published
      by a human.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/about/team/">Meet the team &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>How We Work</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative is <strong>human-directed and AI-collaborated</strong>.
      We believe this transparency strengthens — rather than weakens — the
      credibility of governance work. We use AI tools in our work and we are
      transparent about it.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/about/how-we-work/">Learn about our methodology &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr />

  <section>
    <h2>Funding &amp; Support</h2>
    <p>
      The AEGIS Initiative is currently <strong>privately funded by its founder</strong>.
      All infrastructure, research, publication, and development costs are borne
      by the organization's sole principal. There are no external investors,
      corporate sponsors, or grant funding at this time.
    </p>
    <p>
      We are actively seeking funding, sponsorships, and partnerships to sustain
      and expand this work. If your organization believes in governance-first AI
      security, we'd like to talk.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a href="/about/funding/">Learn how to support AEGIS &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>
